two-year-old Registered Hereford\nBulls for sale. E. H. Bodley. Hobson. Mont.\nlraNETpnr^RAnr^OpUorrTooo^bir*wheat\nOnly Sil. No further risk. Opportunity large\nprofit. Particulars FREE. Midwest Brokerage,\ngIS-W Fleming Bldg., Des Moines, lowa.\nBr'LF-PROPELLED 18-foot Holt combine, 55\nh. p. motor; splendid condition; bargain.\nW. F. Gauger. Davenport. Wash.\nFREE\u2014A little booklet entitled \u201cKillefer Till\nage\u201d which fully describes how the farmins\nof difficult soil is being successfully done and\nhow successful farming has been accomplished\nunder dry. but climatic conditions found in\nmany parts of the world. Write the Connelly\nMachinery Co., of Billings, Montana, for this\nfree booklet.\nBABY CHICKS are worth what you pay for\nthem. Pelkey\u2019s Producers are not cut-price\nChicks, but at these prices they are the best\npoultry investment you can make: Leghorns,\nAnconas, 12c: all Heavy breeds 15c. Four,\neight, ten-weeks old Chicks, all breeds, healthy,\nhusky, priced right. Delivered postpaid, alive.\nguality feeds, supplies. Pelkey\u2019s Poultry and\nhick Farm. Fargo. N. _D.\nNEW LOW PRICES June Quality Chicks, alive.\npostpaid: Anconas. Leghorns 10c: S. C. Reds.\nBarred Rocks 13c: R. C. Reds. White F.ocks,\nWyandottes. Minorcas. Orpingtons 14c: Brah\nmas, 16c: Heavy Mixed 10c. Other standard\nbreeds: full line feed, supplies. Satisfaction\nguaranteed. Rust's Hatchery, Dept. MA. Fargo,\nN. D. _\nDAY-OLD tested June Chicks per 100 prepaid:\nLeghorns $10: Barred. White. But! Rocks,\nBuff and White Orpingtons, Reds. Wyandottes.\nBrahmas $13.50; Mixed $9; All Heavy Mixed\nsll. Lots of 50. >jc more. Orders promptly\nfilled. Bopp Hatchery. Fergus Falls. Minn._\nBABY CHICKS, a hatch every week. Reds,\nRocks. Orpingtons. Minorcas. Leghorns,\nWhite Wyandottes. La ger' s Ha tc he ry. He lena.\nANj^imOinJCE^UANTED^_ _\nWS^ARE^NTTH^MARKEFevery^day^foruve\nchickens, turkeys, ducks and geese. Also ship\nua your dressed veal. hogs and mutton. Hlgh-\nMt market prices paid according to quality on\nday of arrival Montana Meat and Commls\nmcn Co., Butte, Mont.\nPLANTS. BULBS AND SHRUBS\nfllTE\u00dfT\u00a3AJiTS'3>ansFplanU^^\nAsters 4 dosen SI. Pansies 3 dozen SI.. An\nnuals, Perennials. Novelties. We pay deliv\nery. .Bend for Garden Guide. View Acres,\nHamilton, Montana. H. E. Jones.\nSILVER BLACK FOX LITTER arriving at cele\nbrated ^Maclntyre Ranch. Bathurst. New\nBrunswick, Canada, where highest grade and\nmost prized silver fox furs In the world are\nproduced; secure your Registered proven breed\nera pair now, and own them and their pups\nwhan they come. 100 per cent and upwards\nguaranteed. Deferred payment plan. Ranch\nuig facilities afforded, with full information\nhow to feed and care for foxes. Can take few\n\u25a0elected young summer guests for camping,\nhunting, salt water fishing, boating, bathing.\nD. A. Maclntyre, Bathurst, N. B\u201e Canada.\nBAlJEDbluejofntoralfalfaha^^\nAddress Box 40. Bainville, Mont.\nFRjnTpiRECTFRpM'^GROWERS^Iurax^^\n_ rtM- June, two dollars crate of 24 pints;\nLoganberries June, July, two dollars crate:\nBing and Royal Ann Cherries. June, July, two\ndollars crate of twenty pounds: Red Raspber\nries. June, July, two dollars twenty-five cents\ncrate; Black Raspberries June, two dollars fifty\ncents crate. All F. O. B. Canby. Express about\nthree cents pound. Safe arrival guaranteed.\nAgents wanted. Canby Seed and Fruit Com\npany. Canby. Oregon.\nStrawberries, currants, raspberries, peaches.\n_ cherries, apricots. Get list low direct from\nfarm Pricej. R. Schaefer. Vcradale. Wn.\nSTZ T ZTT DOGS FOR MALE\nR^IBTERED tJ \u00dfuMlanWolfhmmd Jr pu^^\nbrothers end sisters to the Blue Ribbon win\nners at Mlles City show. Mrs. Sam White,\nMarmarth. North Dak^\nGERMAN Police pups. Grand Champion stock.\n$25 and up. Photos. Leland Parlch, Bell\ningham. Wash.. 2716 Peabodv.\nFREEnnclcetT'tc^Vppflcants^for^cri^^\nala. Ramsey Stamp Co.. Starkweather. N. D.\nHOUSEWIVES\u2014Bend, for an 8-ounce can of\nKlenotene. (non-inflammable gasoline mix\nture) for cleaning. No danger from fire or\nexplosion. 50 cents postpaid. Agents wanted.\nKlenolene Mfa. Co.. Cascade. Montana.\nWE HAVE\u2019A HIGH-GRADE PIANO left on our\nhands In your town. We will sacrifice the\nprice and make terms as low as 110 per\nmonth. If Interested write Box No. 1173.\nmwxane. Wash.\nIF YOU HAVE ANYTHING YOU WANT TO\n_ oeil or buy, write us and we will tell you\nbow to get In touch with the people you want\nto do business with. Write M. N. A., Box 891,\nGreat Falls. Moatana.\nnBMinCD Frwlinotratw B M k\"M\u201d\nlIBIWuEn D\u00bb. WNllamt \u2022\u25a0naUrlum,\nWwwi wBFBBB Mlnnaapelte. Mln*.\nKSEESSSf\nMANfT\u00dflOHfaUrMllvijmeml^^\nmatrimonial club wish correapendents. De-\nOsa&SL*\u201d 4 Doria Dawn. East\niKafe 8\nDrrBRBBTINa Widow with lam means wishes\nBHROLL NOW FOB BPSEpWRiTrNa. typin',\nbequaerins and tefesraphr. bar, and nl.ht\nsenooL Bposane Tehsraph and-Bu.inei. Instl\ntdW. CTO Rookgry Bids,. Bpoxane.\n^^^m^^Fil^aii^ffiKete^MOJAVF''\n\u25a0ox Ml? Indianapolis. Indiana.\nmsg.\nS^F* \u00ab*awre\nDISaATiariZD married men and women.\n_wrlte me pour problem, i can help you.\ngjrenoe* Larmore, 101 W. Hempstead, rair-\nROMANCX\u2014For rouns .and old. rich and\npoor, men and women from all walks In fife.\n\u25a0end for our lam fist, confidential. People's\nCorrespondence Club. Box 04* Loa Anseles.\nJOIN our elub. Correspond, make friends.\nForay smoke t Bo c J\nJplK Octavius Roy Cohen\nWMirwi \u2014I 11 II II II MIUI II H~T II irrTT\" 111 l\"\n(Published by special arrangement with The?\nChicago Tribune Syndicate)\nIN TWO PARTS\u2014PART TWO\nTHE STORY SO FAB\nJimmy Lynn, a young longshoreman em\nployed on the docks in the Chelsea district\nof New York, engages frequently in thefts\nof merchandise from the waterfront. He\nis considerably discomfited when he finds\nthat his mother is to marry John Shane, a\ndock watchman, and fears that Shane will\ninform his mother of his participation in\nthe thefts. However, Shane does not inter\nfere with Jimmy\u2019s activities. As Shane ap\npears to be very honest, Jimmy is quite in\ndignant when he learns that Shane is to\nassist in the theft of a very valuable case\nof lace. Jimmy remonstrates with Shane,\npointing out the grief and trouble it would\ncause his mother should Shane be appre\nhended. But Shane refers to Jimmy's own\nlife of crime and tells him that what is\ngood for one is good for the other. Jimmy\ndetermines to protect Shane for his moth\ner's sake but has not arrived at a solution\nthe morning the steal is to take place.\nAnd now the story-\nJimmy almost determined to squeal.\nAlmost, but not quite. It would be sim\nple that way; he could go to Chris Dor\ngan, the grizzled pier superintendent,\nand betray the scheme, asking as his re\nward immunity for Shane.\nBut Jimmy knew all along that he\u2019d\nnever go through with that scheme. The\ntenets of the gang had been too deeply\ngraven. Squealing was, to his way of\nif\nThe marriage eccurred. Only a few guests were present and those chiefly neighborhood friends of Kate\u2019s.\nthinking, the one unforgivable sin. Be\nsides, it was grossly dangerous; not that\nJimmy feared danger particularly, but it\nis one thing to fight a menace and quite\nanother to pronounce a sentence of death\nupon one's self.\nEventually a restless and troubled\nslumber came to him, broken at six\no\u2019clock by the wild alarm of the cheap\ntimepiece on the mantel. As he rose\nand stepped into the crude habiliments\nof a longshoreman, he could hear Shane\nlumbering about the next room and then\nthe sound of Kate bustling happily in\nthe kitchen. She was singing softly\u2014\nand while Jimmy would have denied hot\nly that there was any sentimental strain\nin him, the sound of that carefree hum\nming decided him.\nWith the other successful candidates,\nI CLASSIFIED\n\u2014ADVERTISEMENTS\u2014\nfemale help wanted\nWANTED\u2014Raircscntative to sell exclusive Une\nlingerie and sportwear, direct to consumer.\nFor those who can qualify, we have splendid\nopportunity. Wyant Way of New York, Inc-\nJersey City, N. J.\nW\u2019ANTED\nANTIQUES OF EVERY DESCRIPTION. Treas\n_ure House. Wlll7 Ist Ave., Spokane.\n7 ASSAYERS. CHEMISTS. ETC.\nMEWIS WALKER, assayers, chemists, 108\nN. Wyoming, Butte. Mont., Box 114.\nCONSTANT oSWS'S.rt.rs. Earn\nop\u00ab;. isr^MnW BXtVr* 1 Barber\nLOCKSMITH\nWE MAKE ALL KINDS OF KEYS. W. 8.\nDavis, 101 W. Galena. Butte. Mont.\nwool batts\" from A your G own wool.\nPlM\u00bbTONE7\u2019\u2019hot''*BPl^\nCarlsbad; 18 miles from Butte, on the North\nern Pacific Railroad. .Cures rheumatism*\nstomach and kidney trouble. Fifty years rec\nord of cures. Radioactive waters, mud and\nvapor baths. Pipestone Hot Sprints, Pipe\nstone. Montana.\nAUTOMOBILE j3NAP^For^safe?^Becond^*hand^\nsix-cylinder Packard car. 1991. newly refit\nted and in excellent condition, 1425: terms to\none who can give guaranteed paper. This is\n0)e best used car bargain offered this year.\nWrite, Box 891, Great Falls. Mont.\nJa nd UsetTj-eplaceJnenr\u2019pa^\n.A\u00b0L\u00a3S r \u00ae\"J> U uck a savinx of from\n45 to 80 per cent. Prompt attention to mail\norders. Carl Weissman Co., 218 Fourth Sf\nSo.. Auto wrecking House. Gt. Falls. Mont.\nSAVE MONEY\nThree Me pukun, fer SIM. Pwtan 4. extra.\nKAYBEE CO., HOWARD, S. D.\nmOD A Little Booklet Entitled\nMKK. K \"KILLEFER TILLAGE\"\nwhich fully describes how\nthe farmin* of difficult foil la being ene\ncessfully done and how successful farm*\nIns haa been accomplished under dry,\nbut climatic conditions found in many\nparts of the world. Write the\nCONNELLY MACHINERY CO.\nBOXINGS, MONT.. Per this Tree Boeklet\nSe 0.\nHuseth WU\nOptometrl.t and Optielaa\nOBRAT FALLS, MONTANA\nhe started through the gates on to the\nvast, silent pier. At the entrance he en\ncountered the broad shouldered form of\nhis stepfather.\n\u201cShane \u2014you ain\u2019t goln\u2019 through with\nit, are you?\u201d\n\u201cSurest thing you know, Jimmy.\u201d\nJimmy disdained further remarks, but\nas he paused mldwav of the pier his\nthoughts were not of his work, nor of\nthe lace theft about to be negotiated.\nEven when the deck boss\u2014a florid, blus\ntery man\u2014strolled by and whispered out\nof the corner of his mouth that every\nthing was all set, Jimmy merely nodded\nand the superior gentleman was deluded\ninto the belief that Jimmy\u2019s preoccupa\ntion was merely attention to his sup\nposed nefarious labors.\nEight o\u2019clock and work started with a\nscreaming of winches, the thudding of\ncargo as the huge slings kerflumped to\nthe floor of the pier, the clangor and\nclatter and splutter of trucks winding in\nand out through a maze of congested\ntraffic, the hoarse shouts of longshore\nmen and drivers and cargo guards.\nOutside the huge pier trucks were wait\ning patiently in line. Those drivers who\nexpected to be allowed through immedi\nately had already secured preliminary\npasses from the gateman which let them\nthrough to the musty little office of the\ndock boss. There each applied for\u2014and\nwas assigned\u2014a checker from the office\nforce. The checker and driver, in turn,\nreceived their O. K. from the delivery\nclerk and \u2014where the truckload prom\nised to be heavy\u2014the driver returned to\nhis truck and selected a few shenangoes\nfrom the out of workers lounging hope\nfully nearby. Nothing then to do but\nawait the august announcement of John\nShane, the gateman, that there was room\nfor another truck on the pier.\nIt was shortly after the lunch hour\nthat a heavy draft dropped near Jimmy's\nstation. The cargo guard on duty there\nnudged young Mr. Lynn and murmured\ncryptically, \"That\u2019s Itl\u201d Instantly a sig\nnal was flashed down the line and Jimmy\nsaw clearly that his stepfather nodded.\nThe big steal was now about to be put\nInto operation and Jimmy was Immensely\nworried, for. despite his hours of head\nachy thought, he had not yet succeeded\nIn concocting a scheme which would keep\nhis mother's husband from traveling the\nprimrose path.\nWithout even bothering to look, Jimmy\nknew what was happening outside. Out\nyonder a big truck was waiting patiently\nfor a signal from John Shane. This\ntruck was actually the property of a\nwholesale grocery concern and had been\nsent down to remove a large shipment of\nfancy Imported groceries and delicates\nsen stull. The driver was known to, and\ntrusted by. Lew Foster and his cohorts,\nand now, when John Shane nodded, this\nswarthy person swung out of Une, oblivi\nous to the angry shoutings of other\ntruck drivers, and passed through the\ngate with his particular checker\u2014a pale,\nanemic looking young chap who had also\nlistened to the siren call of easv money.\nUnder the watchful eye of the dishon\nest cargo guard, Jimmy slipped his hand\ntruck under the case of lace and trun\ndled it halfway across the pier. He un\nloaded near a pile of cargo\u2014which he\nknew was the cargo belonging to the\nwholesale grocery concern. The watch\nman, anxious to appear Innocent, strolled\naway that he might not see what was\nabout to happen.\nThe grocery truck appeared with the\ncomplaisant checker and greasy shenan\ngoes. Cases of the delicacies were loaded\nconspicuously around the outside of the\ntruck, and then, with Jimmy's personal\nassistance\u2014the case of lace was hoisted\naboard, and immediately surrounded by\nmore groceries.\nSo much, then, for that. Jimmy\nglanced toward the entrance and saw the\namused eye of his stepfather focused up\non him. Jimmy was desperate. He was\nnot opposed to thievery, as such, but he\nwas decidedly averse to having John\nShane sent to prison\u2014and the company\nwhich owned the Agrarla was most dis\nconcertingly summary in its manner of\ndealing with persons detected in the act\nof stealing.\nThe chances are that Jimmy had never\nheard the adage about necessity being\nthe maternal forbear of invention. The\nfact remains, however, that It Is. In a\nblinding white light of clear thinking\nthe solution of the problem presented\nitself. It was a scheme rarely and su\nperbly beautiful and, while It embodied\na certain degree of physical discomfort\nfor a comparatively Innocent person,\nJimmy was not a young man to let such\na detail deter him from a proper and\nefficient course of action.\nHe was smiling as he stepped close to\nthe swarthy truck driver who had come\nfor his groceries\u2014and Lew Foster's case\nof lace. There was, In his manner, no\nslightest hint of what he Intended\u2014but\nIn the fraction of a minute which had\nalready elapsed since the Idea had first\nblossomed, every little detail was clear\nin Jimmy's mind.\n\"Swell weather, ain\u2019t It?\" remarked\nJimmy casually to the truck driver.\n\"Yeh\u2014it sure is,\" agreed that gentle\nman. Whereupon, with the deftness\nand snap of a professional pugilist, Jim\nmy landed on that portion of the truck\ndriver's cranial apparatus which is known\nas the button I\nPOPLAR STANDARD\nEven before the briefly amazed and to\ntally unconscious driver hit the floor of\nthe pier, bedlam broke loose. Some one\nyelled \u201cFight!\u201d There was a wild rush\nof longshoremen, cargo guards, and cus-\ntoms men to the scene of action.\nAnd there was action aplenty for a\nfew seconds. Jimmy venomously threw\nhimself on the prostrate form of the un\nfortunate truck driver and wrestled\nmightily. When he rose it was to stare\ninto a ring of excited faces, marking\nparticularly the watchman who had been\nfixed, the anemic checker who was trem\nbling, and two or three members of the\nChelsea gang who stared open mouthed.\nJimmy spoke harshly of his late op\nponent\u2019s ancestry and informed the by\nstanders that the man had foully insult\ned him. \u201cI just hadda hit him, fellers,\u201d\ndefended Mr. Lynn. \u201cI sure did.\u201d\nA hoarse voice grated in Jimmy\u2019s ear.\n\u201cYou played hell \u2014that\u2019s what you done.\nThat bird has got the fake pass your old\nman give him \u2014and now we can't get this\ntruck off the pier.\u201d\nJimmy was laughing to himself. Here\nwas thrill and adventure \u2014and triumph\nof which his gangmates knew nothing.\nThe danger to John Shane had been the\ndiscovery of his participation. It was all\nvery well to say that should discovery en\nsue, the checker would be the victim of\nlegal wrath\u2014but there wu alway. the\npossibility that some one possessing\nkeenness of mind might Inquire too\nclosely Into why the gateman accepted a\nfake pass\u2014and why he let a case of lace\nthrough on a grocery truck without hav\ning his suspicions aroused.\nBut now the little transaction had\nbeen thoroughly spoiled. There would\nbe no fake pass presented. In spite of\nhis best Intentions, John Shane was not\na party to what might happsn\u2014where\nfore Jimmy was as eager as any of his\nfellows successfully to conclude the theft.\nHe crossed to one of his Intimates and\nspoke softly Into that gentleman's ear.\n\u201cGet the gang togetherl\" he ordered.\n\"I'll drive the damned truck and we\u2019ll\nrush the gate.\"\nIt was a daring, desperate thing; but\nthe Chelsea gang was not unused to dar\ning deeds. Besides, the sheer melodra\nmatic picturesqueness of it made an Ir\nrestlble appeal. The word spread swiftly.\nAt a signal from Jimmy, seven of the\nChelaealtes leaped for the grocery truck\n\u2014the motor of which was still thrum\nming. Jimmy took the wheel, let his\ngears Into low. gave one sonorous blast\nof the siren, and stepped on the gas.\nThe effect was Immediate and startling.\nAll other noises on the pier were drowned\nin the banging of the motor. Long\nshoremen and cargo guards leaped out of\nthe way\u2014yelling. Truck driven cursed\nfrantically and backed their vehicles Into\nthe cargo piles. And at the pier entrance\nsomething was happening.\nJohn Shane's eyes narrowed, and he\nturned away briefly to beckon to three\nbroad shouldered, silent men who had\nbeen lounging nearby. With expert eyes,\nthis quartet sized up the situation.\nLunging toward them was the massive\ntrack. At the wheel was Jimmy Lynn,\nhandsome face set and stern. Beside him\nwas a squat, ratty little man, and in the\nsteady right hand of that man was an\nexceedingly businesslike blue steel auto\nmatic.\nTwo gangsters clung precariously to\nthe tall of the truck. They held with\ntheir left hands and In their rights were\nwicked, curving bale hooks, modern scim\nitars of the waterfront: dangerous weap\nons In these expert hands. Lying ready\non top of the truck were three others of\nthe gang and one of these had also pro\nduced a gun.\nWork had stopped as by magic. Long\nshoremen, crew, and officers flocked to\nthe rail of the massive and graceful\nAgrarla to witness the battle. There was\na moment of thunder as the truck bore\ndown on the gate: a tense, fierce wait\ning for the first spitting of a gun, and\nthen, clear above the roar of the truck\u2014\nJimmy Lynn\u2019s warning to his stepfather:\n\"Out of the way\u2014or there'll be a\nkillin\u2019l\"\nThe four men at the gate were un\narmed. They were brave but not unduly\nfoolish. They stepped back and the truck\nbludgeoned through and whirled into\nthe congested traffic of West street. The\nthree square shouldered men who had\nstood with John Shane followed.\nJimmy gave a demonstration of deft\nand daring driving. He careened across\nWest street, avoiding trucks and taxicabs\nby inches; cursing, pleading, never slow\ning for an instant. Two traffic police\nmen yelled at him, but he paid them no\nheed. A side street yawned Its welcome\nand he darted into it. Not until then\ndid the desperate crew of the truck relax.\nThey looked at each other and grinned\nin somewhat sickly fashion\u2014victims to\nreaction.\nJimmy strung two more corners, then\nslowed down. He spoke curtly to his fel\nlows, as befits a Napoleon of felony. Then,\nwith soma slight regard for traffic regu\nlations. he headed toward the apparently\ninnocent warehouse where Lew Foster\nand his crowd stored valuable material\nunconventionally obtained and dis\nposed of It at their leisure.\neases\nOn the second deck of the pier, in an\nexpensive mahogany furnished office,\nChris Dorgan, pier superintendent, nod-\nded enthusiastically at the report of\nJohn Shane, gateman.\n\u201cSorry I missed it, John. I could hear\nthe noise up here. 'Frald to move,\nthough; might have looked funny.\u201d\nShane\u2019s eyes were dancing. \u201cThe kid\nthat drove the truck is chockful of nerve.\nI didn\u2019t know what was wrong when I\nsaw him bust that truck driver. Funny\nthing, too. I been talkin\u2019 with that bird,\nan\u2019 he\u2019s sore as a boil. Says the lad just\ncome along, said somethin* about it bein\na nice day and then socked him one.\u201d\nDorgan tapped spatulate fingers on the\ndesk top. \u201cSpot any of the bunch, John?\u201d\n\u201cYeh\u2014sure.\u201d Shane was honest. \u201cBut\nI ain't gonna spill no names. I warned\nyou that day before yesterday when they\nfirst came to me.\u201d\n\u2019Sall right.\u201d Dorgan grinned under\nstandlngly. \u201cArresting a few longshore\nmen isn\u2019t going to help us a bit. Every\ntime we try that some blasted cheap poli\ntician gets \u2019em out of jail before the\ndoors are locked behind \u2019em. The birds\nwe\u2019re after are the ones that handle the\nbig stuff\u2014like this lace, for instance\nShane walked from the office of his\nsuperintendent. He was well pleased, not\nalone with what had happened in con\nnection with the lace theft, but because\nthe motives behind the action of his\nstepson had been crystal clear. Of course,\nthe lad believed that he had accepted\nLew Foster\u2019s bribe in good faith.\nJohn was smiling to himself through the\nrest of the day, and he was still smiling\nwhen he reached the little flat that night\nand went into the tiny bathroom to wash\nup.\nInto that bathroom stormed Jimmy\nLynn, frowning and furious\u2014and Jimmy\ndid not mince words.\n\u201cNow listen here, Shane: What I done\nthis afternoon was to keep you from\nmaking a damned fool of yourself. I\nwasn\u2019t gonna see you get nabbed in that\ndeal \u2014and the only thing left was to rush\nthe gate.\u201d\nShane was quietly argumentative. \u201cI\nguess I can look out for myself, Jimmy.\u201d\n\u201cLike thunder you can! Far as steal\ning is concerned \u2014you\u2019re a sucker. You\ndon\u2019t know nothin* about it. Now I\u2019m\nasking you\u2014man to man\u2014for mom\u2019s\nsake, anyway\u2014to lay off it from now on.\u201d\nThe older man shrugged and turned\naway. \u201cNothin\u2019 stirring, Jimmy. If you\ncan grab off a lot of that soft money, so\ncan I.\u201d\n\u201cYou\u2019re talkin' like a fool, John Shane.\nIf things had gone through like they was\nplanned this afternoon you\u2019d have been\nin stir right now.\u201d\n\u201cAin\u2019t you kind of exaggerating,\nJimmy?\u201d\n\u201cNo, I\u2019m not. They was wise to that\nwhole business\u2014must have been, because\nthe truck was followed. And no sooner\nhad we dumped the lace in Lew Foster\u2019s\nwarehouse than a whole gang of bulls lit\non us. We got away, but they grabbed\nLew an\u2019 two of his rich friends. Now\njust suppose they hadn\u2019t thought you\nwas all right on account of us breaking\nthrough and makin\u2019 it seem good? Sup\npose that?\u201d\nJohn Shane shook his head. \u201cIf things\nhad gone according to schedule, I guess\nthey wouldn't have followed the truck.\nNo, Jimmy\u2014l got the hunch there\u2019s a\nlot of money to be picked up in a job\nlike I got. And I guess whatever is all\nokay for you is good enough for me.\u201d\nThe boy\u2019s lips opened, then closed\nagain. From the dining room came the\nclatter of crockery as Kate set the table\nfor their evening meal. It Is hard to say\nJust what vision crossed the boy\u2019s mind\nthen but suddenly he caught the\nother man by the shoulder and whirled\nhim around.\n\u201cYou mean,\u201d he rasped, \u201cthat if I\u2019ll go\nstraight\u2014you will?\u201d\n\u201cUh-huh. Sure.\u201d\n\u201cYou swear it?\u201d\n\u201cYeh. Jimmy\u2014l do.\u201d\nJimmy\u2019s hand came out. \u201cDone with\nyou!\u201d he cried, \u201cFrom this minute on!\u201d\nAnd John Shane, who had never in his\nlife known a dishonest thought or com\nmitted a dishonest deed, shook hands\nwith Jimmy Lynn\u2014did it solemnly and\nseriously\u2014and promised that he would\nreform. But somehow, the situation did\nnot strike him as funny and as\nthey walked into the dining room to\ngether he dropped an affectionate, pa\nternal arm about the broad shoulders of\nhis son.\n(Copyright: 1926: By Octavus Roy Cohen)\nFreshen a Heavy Skin\nWith the antiseptic, fascinating Cutl\ncora Talcum Powder, un exquisitely\nscented, economical face, skin, baby\nand dusting powder and perfume.\nRenders other perfumes suiierlluoiis.\nOne of the Cutlcura Toilet Trio (Soap,\nOintment. Talcum). \u2014Advertisement.\ni\nSaves Tot from Drowning\nJohn Lovell, small son of Mr. and Mrs.\nEdward Lovell. Anaconda, proved to be\na real hero a few days ago when he\nJumped in Warm Springs creek to rescue\nfive-year-old Reccla May Evans who was\nstruggling in the water into which she\nhad fallen and was unable to get to the\nshore. When the Lovell boy got the girl\nto the side of the rushing creek she was\nunconscious. After first aid treatment\nhad been given her she was taken to\nthe homo of her parents, who gratefully\nrewarded the little hero.\nBE sure to use Car-\nnat on Mi,lt n pud\ndings. It gives them r x 'i-\u201c.\nIBH auch su P er or rich\nneM flavor and\nture. In fact, Carna\nt*on makes milk\nH dishes better. And\n.y fa*\u2122 y\u00b0 u tried in\ngHH|| coffee?\nWrit, f,r C\"!t\nIM wat&w '\u25a0gHCjsMKii\nlIBS CamitloD Milk Products\nTHREE MILLION FOR\nSTATE HIGHWAYS\nSTATE HIGHWAY COMMISSION WILL\nSPEND VAST SUM DURING\nFISCAL YEAR\nRailways Oppose Bus Application; 17,725\nAcres of Lieu Lands Given to Montana;\nMuch School Construction Planned for\nthis Year\n(By Our Helena Correspondent)\nMontana will spend $3,000.0dd on\ngood roads during the fiscal year be\nginning July 1 and ending June 30,\n1928, James 11. Rowe, state highway\ncommissioner, said on the eve of at\ntending a joint meeting of the high\nway commission and bureau of good\nroads officials at Helena.\nSilver Bow county\u2019s 1927-28 $400,000\nhighway program will be approved by\nthe commission at the Helena session,\nRowe said. The Woodville road and the\nproject from the Five-Mile house to the\nfoot of Harding way comprise the two\nSliver Bow projects. Both roads will be\nconstructed and graveled this year and\npavement will be laid next year, giving\nthe road beds a full season's travel to\nfiermlt the ground to settle. This will\nnsure the life of the highway for sev\neral years, engineers who surveyed the\nprojects declared.\nThe highway commission and the bu\nreau of good roads officials will map out\nthe road building campaign for Montana\nfor next year at the Helena meeting. The\nstate Is divided into two divisions with\n12 districts in the divisions. Silver Bow\ncounty and the southern part of the\nstate are in the second division, while\nthe northern tier of counties comprise\nthe first division.\nContracts for highway construction\nwork in division one will be let at the\nHelena meeting, Rowe said. While the\nhighway commissioner did not know\nwhat the exact projects were he said the\nstate and northern counties were active\nin good roads work this year. The fed\neral government is also building a road\nthrough Glacier park, making it possible\nto drive through the entire park. This\nwork was begun several years ago and\nwill be completed this summer.\n\nProtest against the application of John\nH. Gibson to operate motor freight and\nEassenger service between Harlowton and\newlstown has been filed by the Great\nNorthern and Milwaukee railways and\nthe American Railway Express. The ex\npress company and the Northern Pacific\nalso filed protest with the Montana rail\nroad commission against the application\nof T. R. Hudgln to operate motor freight\nservice between Pompey's Pillar and Wor\nden with occasional trips to Billings.\n\nThrough the efforts of Senator Walsh,\nthe state has gained possession of 17,-\n725.13 acres of lieu lands formerly held\nunder the Carey land act, according to\nI. M. Brandjord, register of state lands.\nThe state land office has been notified\nthat the secretary of interior and com\nmissioner of the general land offices have\nauthorized the Great Falls land office to\naccept the filings by the state land com\nmission on this land, which Is located in\nPondera and Cascade counties.\n\u201cThese lands were relinquished by the\nCarey Act board of the state of Montana\non May 1, 1926,\u201d said Mr. Brandjord,\n\u201cand the state board of land commis\nsioners attempted to select the lands as\nHeu lands for others lost to the state at\nthe same time, but met with legal diffi\nculties.\n\u201cSenator Walsh Introduced a bill in\nthe senate granting to the state of Mon\ntana preference right to select these\nlands for others lost to the state and\nthis act was approved by President Cool\nidge, January 1, 1927. Under the pro\nvisions of the act the general land office\nhas now authorized the Great Falls of\nfice to accept the filings on behalf of\nthe state and the lengthy and some\nwhat laborious proceedings on the part\nof the state are brought to a successful\ndetermination.\u201d\nConstruction activity in Montana has\ntoken on new life this spring, according\nto I. M. Brandjord. register of state lands,\nwho declared that several new school\nhouses were being planned and bond\nIssues being contemplated.\n\u201cSchool district No. 35 of Judith Basin\ncounty and district No. 70 of Fergus\ncounty, which jointly embraces the town\nof Buffalo, is making plans for erecting\na modern school building during the\nsummer,\" said Mr. Brandjord. \"Several\nthousand dollars have been accumulated\nIn the treasury of school districts and an\nelection held authorized the Issuance of\namortization bonds In the amount of\n*25,000 to furnish the balance of neces\nsary capital.\n'The Hobson school district In Judith\nBasin county Is also contemplating the\nerection of a new school bpllding and\nan Issuance of *40,000 In bonds Is being\nconsidered.\n\"Several substantial new school build\nings will also bo erected in Valley coun\nty which will be financed through the\nIssuance of building bonds. The state\nwill no doubt make blds on all these\nbond Issues.\"\nMONTANA OIL FIELD\nLARGEST IN WORLD\nNORTHERN AREA WITH 50,000 PROVEN\nACRES HAS ONLY BEEN\nSCRATCHED\nWells in This State Produce Double the\nAverage; State Leads In Both OH and\nGas; Kevin-Sunburst Field Comprises\n250,000 Acres\nMontana's greatest oil field, the\nKevin-Sunburst, said to be one of the\nlargest structures in the world, now\nhas 700 active wells. Since its discov\nery In Marc]), 1922, this field has pro\nduced over 10.000,000 barrels of oil, val\nued at more than $13,000,000.\nAt the close of last year 600 wells were\nlisted in the field, which produced 6,463,-\n352 barrels of crude oil or about 10,700\nbarrels per well. This means an average\nof 29 barrels of oil daily for each of the\n600 wells or a daily value of $12,000.\nKevin-Sunburst was the fifth field in\nMontana in which oil was discovered.\nDuring the year of its discovery, there\nwere reported 27 producing wells in the\nfield with a production of 28.987.48 bar\nrels for the year. The following year\nthere were 146 wells and a production of\n441.531.48 barrels. In 1924 there were 220\nwells in the field and In 1925 there were\n438. Production in 1926 of 6,463,352 bar\nrels was valued at 87.548,114.\nBoth Oil and Gas\nThe Kevin-Sunburst structure is pecu\nliar in that most of the wells on the\nnorth side of the dome, if drilled to the\nbasal sand of the Ellis, show at least\ntraces of oil or gas in one or more of the\nsands and most of them have been oil\nproducers, whereas those on the south\nside have yielded gas usually from the\nSunburst or higher sands and only very\nsmall traces of oil. To date gas has not\nbeen the objective of exploration in this\nfield, but even so, an important gas field\nhas been found to exist on the south\nside of the dome, and considerable quan\ntities of gas are also being produced\nalong with the oil from areas farther\nnorth.\nThe oil from the Sunburst sand has a\ndark color, an odor like that of gasoline,\nand a gravity of about 35 degrees Baume.\nThe Sunburst, the second well to be\nbrought in in the Kevin-Sunburst field,\nencountered oil 200 to 250 feet above the\nbasal sand of the Ellis and was struck at\na depth of only 1,550 feet. In 1926 the\nGreat Northern railroad purchased\n2,555.410 barrels of fuel oil, produced\nfrom the Kevin-Sunburst fields.\n250,000 ill Field\nThat Montana has the largest oil field\nin the world. Is the opinion of L. C.\nStevenson, president of the Sunburst Oil\nand Refining company. \u201cThe oil field in\nnorthern Montana,\u201d says Mr. Stevenson,\n\u2019\u2019comprises 250.000 acres with a probable\narea of 50.000 acres proven for oil pools.\nThe field has only been scratched.\u201d\nThe Montana natural resource bulletin\npublished by the Montana Stock and\nBond company, in quoting Mr. Steven\nson as above, points out that in addition\nto the acres under drilling operations or\nthose proven for pools there are 150,000\nacres more of which probably 60,000 acres\nhave been proven for gas.\nThe value of Montana crude oil last\nyear was more than 810,000.000 from a\nproduction of 7.530.587 barrels produced\nin the four fields. Cat Creek. Kevin-Sun\nburst. Lake Basin, and Elk Basin, accord\ning to the state publicity division. This\nis an increase of approximately 84.000,000\nover 1925. The value for 1925 was\n$6,461,000.\nMontana produces, on the average,\nmore than twice as much oil per well as\nthe average for all wells in the United\nStates. Montana's average from 856\nwells being 16.8 barrels per well and the\nnational average from 214,259 wells being\nonly 7.8 barrels.\nPROSPERITY FOR\nWEST FORESEEN\nUNION PACIFIC OFFICIAL PAINTS\nALLURING PICTURE OF\nFUTURE MONTHS\nFrank W. Robinson, Vice-President of Big\nRall Corporation, Says Business Out\nlook Is as Good as Ilas Been Seen in\nMany Years\n\"The business outlook In the West\nIs much lietter than last year and as\ngood ns anything we have seen in many\nyears.\u201d This Is the statement of Frank\nW. Robinson, vice president In charge\nof traffic of the Union Pacific system,\nwhich Includes the Oregon Short Line,\nOregon-Uaslilngton Railway Naviga\ntion company. Los Angeles Salt Lake\nRailroad company and the St. Joseph\nGrand Island Railway company, as\nwell us the Union Pacific proper. In\nhis statement regarding the business\noutlook. Mr. Robinson said he was\nsfieuklng from the standpoint of con\nditions along the lines of the entire\nU. P. system.\n\u201cThe mining industry Is holding Its\nown.\" he said, \"and the agricultural\ncondition Is good with prices improving.\nPrices arc not what the farmers feel they\nshould be, but the situation Is righting\nItself with every likelihood of tine crops\nthis year.\n\"The condition of the mining Indus\ntry,\" Mr. Robinson continued. \"Is due to\ngreater efficiency and the development\nof metallurgical science.\n\"Formerly lead ores were penalized for\ntheir zinc content. Today zinc is an\nImportant metal. The skUl shown In ths\ntreatment of complex ores, the larger\npercentage of recoveries and the efficient\nmanner in which ores are mined, trans\nported. milled, reduced and refined, have\nmade It possible for the mining Industry\nto make a good showing in the face of a\nsomewhat unfavorable market.\n\"Cattle are good and sheep are excep\ntionally good. The best cattle In the\nworld, to my notion, are raised in the\nBig Hole basin. The Big Hole and the\nGrangeville. Idaho, district are two of\nthe best cattle areas to be found any\nwhere.\u201d\nThe recent visit was Mr. Robinson\u2019s first\ntrip to Butte in seven years. Previous to\nIlls removal to Omaha he was estab\nlished at Portland. Ore.\nDiscussing expenditures of the road,\nhe said: \"We are always spending. It\ncosts us 43,000 for each mile of track\nevery year tn maintenance.\n\"we are spending about 12,000,000 thia\nyear on equipment. We have bought\nnumber or passenger cars of the latest\nand best design and a number of freight\ncars, which include steel horse cars.\u201d\nAlthough serving a wide agricultural\narea. Mr. Robinson stated that not Issa\nthan 25 per cent of the business of the\nUnion Pacific is made up of mines ship\nments.\n\"We are much interested in the pros\nperity of the mining Industry and par\nticularly In the welfare of Butte,\u201d Mr.\nRobinson stated. \"Our business from\nthis city add district haa been satisfac\ntory. It has shown Butte to bo in\nmuch better condition industrially and\ncommercially than many cities of larger\nsize.\nLuundrymen Choose Billings\nBillings was selected as the next meet\ning place of the State Laundrymen's as\nsociation. Joseph Burns of Butte was\nselected president. Robert Pauline, vtoe\npresident; Ouy Davidson of Butte, 107\nelected secretary; Fred Chapman. DtlloM,\nsergeant-at-arms. O. A. Debisr, Omak\nFalls, retiring president, was made n\nmember of the regional board of tho na\ntional association. Preparations worn\nmade to protest, through tho state HR\nroad commission, against a raise in en\npress rates on laundry, aaeortod tB\namount to 28 per cent.","height":"22452","width":"18296"}}
